<Content>Great staff, typical Westin -- Skip the restaurant I like Westin Hotels, the beds, the showers and the drinks. The staff was fantastic, friendly helpful, far above expectations.The hotel is a way from Boston and beware of walking distances -- what was described as a 1/4 mile walk was really 2 miles, they are a walking city so take good shoes. There aren't a lot of restaurants in the area so you end up tacking a pretty pricy cab ride onto any trip. Most rooms do have a pretty view of the water.This hotel fails on it's restaurant -- Sauciety -- a play on words combining sauce and society. Seriously -- can they stop trying so hard to invent things. When you are traveling if you are so tired you are eating in the hotel restaurant, you don't want some weird crap on your plate. We ordered off the menu instead of the buffet for breakfast and were punished with the typical hotel 25 minute wait for your food, then our eggs were over cooked, while I recognize the need to put vinegar in the poaching water, I think they forgot the water and then they served home fries which were so overseasoned with some southwest mix they could not be eaten. We tried our luck a second time for lunch. Had a WONDERFUL mushroom bisque soup and a burger which was buried under some concoction of onion sugar and vinegar that was ICE cold. Who wants their hot food doused with an ice cold sauce? It was AWFUL and lunch for two people, two burgers, two cups of soup and two waters was over $60 -- which is insane. The atmosphere did not warrant that nor did the food quality.Accolades to the front desk staff -- go find a new chef! 
