<Content>It's a bit of a walk, but I liked it. The Westin Boston Waterfront is a newer hotel that is still going through some construction. My wife and I stayed in a standard room with a King size bed. Let me tell you, these beds rock! The room is great. We had absolutely no problems with it. There is a subway/bus station fairly close so you'll have to take that walk everytime you plan on going anywhere. No big deal though, unless you have problems walking. We bought a weekly subway pass and once we figured out the subway system getting around was a breeze. The pass will get you a bus ride from the airport that will drop you off fairly close to the hotel. Again, you'll have a bit of a walk so if you have a lot of bags or will have trouble walking your bag about 100 yards to the hotel you should get a cab. Be sure to hit the Freedom Trail and eat a lot of Italian food inn the North End. Our favorite of three nights dining was Dolce Vita. And be sure to stop at Mike's Pastries and get a Neapolitan. Unbelievable.Boston was a blast and this hotel was extremely nice. Only one restaurant in the hotel and not many close by. You'll have to take the subway to get anywhere really worth eating at. One other note, if you have trouble walking or are confined to a wheelchair then city may not be the best choice of a vacation for you. Unfortunately, our founding fathers did not anticipate the need for handicapped accessible buildings . 
