<Content>Off the beaten track but nice We stayed at the Westin Waterfront because we were going to see my son at college (Berklee) and got a decent price on Hotwire. Overall this is a nice hotel - four stars is not too much of a stretch, though three or three and one-half is probably more realistic. Our room was extremely clean - nice flat screen tv - comfy beds, immaculate bathroom (crucial). My wife commented that it seemed brand new, which may be the case based on reviews here discussing recent removations. Only real drawbacks of the hotel itself are 1. walking past all the yuppies with square glasses in the lobby, and 2. the fact that absolutely nothing is free (want some water - there's a $5 bottle in your room; Wi-fi? All yours for the low price of $7.99 for 24-hours. Parking? About $30 a day above the price of the room, but this is Boston). For the price you'd think they'd could toss a bottle of agua in, huh? The real drawback to this particular Westin is that it's off the beaten path - you can SEE Boston from the hotel but getting there is a bit of a trip. We took the subway which is about a quarter mile walk past dark warehouses to the South Station, then two trains to get to the Back Bay. Tolerable, but I wouldn't want to do it in January. If you're in Boston for a conference this is a perfect hotel since the monster of a Convention Center is right next door and the hotel is a quality one. But if you're looking to see Boston you might want to look for something a little closer to the action. Oh, also map it out, it's a little challenging to find, and calling the hotel for directions is like calling Fidel Castro for an encouraging discussion on democracy. Pretty useless. 
